Researchers found that maintaining a serum level associated with a 50 percent reduction in cancer risk can be achieved by taking 2,000 international units of vitamin D3 daily and spending 10 to 15 minutes in the sun.
Different skin tones may require varying sun exposure times.
Studies showed that higher vitamin D levels correlate with lower cancer rates, particularly breast and colorectal cancer.
Recommendations include daily vitamin D supplements and regular sun exposure.
The study emphasizes the importance of vitamin D in preventing various cancers and suggests increasing intake through diet, supplements, and sunlight exposure.
